Step-by-Step Guide for Manually Committing and Pushing Changes:
1. Check for Modified Files
First, check which files have been modified in your repository:

bash
*git status
This will show all the modified files, as well as any new untracked files.

2. Stage the Changes
To stage all the modified files, use the git add command. This prepares them to be committed.
bash
*git add .
The . will stage all modified and new files. If you only want to stage specific files, you can do so by naming them individually:

bash
*git add filename

3. Commit the Changes
After staging, commit the changes with a message describing what was modified.
bash
*git commit -m "Your commit message here"

Example:
bash
*git commit -m "Updated the homepage content"
The -m option allows you to add a commit message directly in the command.

4. Push the Changes
After committing, push your changes to the remote GitHub repository.
bash
*git push origin main
This pushes your changes to the main branch. If you're using a different branch, replace main with the appropriate branch name.

5. Verify the Push
After pushing, you can check on GitHub or use:

bash
*git log
This will show you the commit history and confirm that your changes were pushed successfully.
